# Mongoose & MongoDB Standards

## Schema Design

- Use appropriate data types
- Add required fields
- Use indexes for frequently queried fields
- Set default values where appropriate
- Use virtuals for computed properties

## Validation

- Use Mongoose built-in validators
- Add custom validators when needed
- Use Joi for complex validation
- Validate on both schema and API level

## Query Optimization

- Use lean() for read-only queries
- Select only needed fields
- Use pagination for large datasets
- Avoid N+1 queries with populate
- Use indexes effectively

---

# Controller Standards

## Error Handling

```javascript
const asyncHandler = require('express-async-handler');

const controller = asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {
  try {
    // Your logic
  } catch (error) {
    // Handle error
  }
});
```

## Validation Pattern

```javascript
const { validateCreate } = require('../models/Model');

const error = validateCreate(req.body);
if (error) {
  return res.status(400).json({ message: error.details[0].message });
}
```

## Response Pattern

```javascript
// Single item
res.status(200).json(data);

// With message
res.status(200).json({ message: 'Success', data });

// With pagination
res.status(200).json({
  data: results,
  meta: { total, page, pages, limit }
});
```

---

# Middleware Standards

## Authentication

- Use JWT tokens
- Verify token on protected routes
- Include user info in req.user
- Handle token expiration gracefully

## Authorization

- Check roles and permissions
- Use role-based access control (RBAC)
- Implement resource-level authorization when needed

## Error Handling

- Use global error handler
- Log errors appropriately
- Return user-friendly messages
- Don't expose stack traces in production

---

# Security Best Practices

## Input Validation

- Never trust user input
- Validate on both client and server
- Sanitize data before storage
- Use prepared statements

## Password Security

- Use bcrypt for hashing
- Minimum 10 rounds
- Never store plain text passwords
- Use strong password policies

## API Security

- Rate limiting
- CORS configuration
- Helmet for security headers
- Sanitize user input
- Protect against SQL injection
- Protect against XSS

## Data Protection

- Encrypt sensitive data
- Use HTTPS in production
- Secure environment variables
- Never commit secrets

